### 1. Key Technical Clues

*   **"C++26 will likely have stackful coroutines... and many other goodies."**
    *   C++ standards are released every three years (C++11, 14, 17, 20, 23, 26...).
    *   As of 2024, C++23 is the current standard. C++26 is the *next* major standard.
    *   The author is speculating about features in C++26 as if they are future possibilities or recently confirmed proposals. This places the text **after C++23 was finalized (late 2023/early 2024)** but **before C++26 is finalized (expected 2026)**.
    *   The mention of "stackful coroutines" is a specific, long-debated feature. In the C++ community, stackful coroutines have been a topic of discussion for years, often contrasted with stackless (async/await). The fact that the author lists them as a likely feature of C++26 suggests they are following the current proposal status. As of mid-2024, stackful coroutines are not guaranteed for C++26 but are still discussed.

*   **"C++20 brings us modules... looking forward to actually being implemented fairly soon."**
    *   C++20 modules were standardized in 2020. However, full, widespread implementation across all major compilers (MSVC, GCC, Clang) has been a gradual process.
    *   The phrase "looking forward to actually being implemented fairly soon" suggests that while the standard exists, the author feels the ecosystem is still catching up. This sentiment was very common in **2021–2023**. However, by 2024, modules are widely considered "available" in modern toolchains, though adoption is still growing. This clue is slightly ambiguous but leans toward the early-mid 2020s.

*   **"Generic associated types have more of the flavor of making combinations of existing features work as expected rather than bringing any fundamentally new capabilities; the forthcoming 'type alias impl trait' is similar."**
    *   **Generic Associated Types (GATs)** were stabilized in Rust **1.65** (May 2023).
    *   **"Type alias impl trait" (TAIT)** was stabilized in Rust **1.75** (March 2024).
    *   The author refers to TAIT as **"forthcoming."** This is the strongest temporal anchor.
    *   Therefore, the text must have been written **before March 2024**, when TAIT was stabilized.
    *   It must have been written **after May 2023**, when GATs were stabilized, because the author is commenting on GATs as a recent, settled feature ("recently landed features such as generic associated types").

*   **"Async has been a major effort, but recently landed features..."**
    *   Rust's async ecosystem (async/await, Pin, etc.) has been evolving since 2018. The "recently landed" comment likely refers to the stabilization of core async primitives and GATs, which enabled more complex async patterns. This fits the 2023–2024 timeframe.

